{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17518185","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17518185"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:01:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:01:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12893"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12893","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12893"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0,0.01,0,0.78]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5331"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77273"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5331","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5331"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12893"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62780"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1903"},{"type":"tags","id":"2843"},{"type":"tags","id":"2852"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"5810"},{"type":"tags","id":"6351"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9059"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9242"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43364"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77273","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77273"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 70-year-old man presents to the clinic with a 2-day history of sudden onset, severe pain and swelling in his right knee. He reports that the pain is worse with movement and is associated with redness, warmth and tenderness. He has no other joint symptoms. The patient has a past medical history of hypertension, hyperlipidaemia and osteoarthritis. He is a current smoker and drinks alcohol socially. He has no family history of arthritis. On examination, the patient\u0027s right knee is swollen, erythematous and tender to palpation. There is a loss of range of movement and there is no effusion. There are no other joint abnormalities. A plain radiograph of the right knee is unremarkable. A joint aspiration is performed and the synovial fluid is examined under a microscope. The fluid contains numerous positively birefringent crystals.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis in this scenario?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Gout","Rheumatoid arthritis","Septic arthritis","Osteoarthritis","Pseudogout"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s presentation, history, examination and investigation findings are all consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Epseudogout\u003C/strong\u003E. Pseudogout, also known as calcium pyrophosphate deposition disease (CPPD), is a crystal arthritis characterized by the deposition of calcium pyrophosphate crystals within the joints that appear as positively birefringent crystals on fluid analysis. It commonly affects the elderly population and presents with acute episodes of joint pain, swelling, and inflammation. The most commonly involved joints include the knees, wrists, and ankles. Patients often describe sudden-onset pain, similar to gout, but unlike gout, pseudogout commonly affects larger joints. The affected joints may appear red, warm, and swollen on examination. Radiographic findings such as chondrocalcinosis, and the presence of calcium pyrophosphate crystals in the joint cartilage, are characteristic of pseudogout. The identification of calcium pyrophosphate crystals in synovial fluid analysis confirms the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERheumatoid arthritis\u003C/strong\u003E is a chronic inflammatory arthritis that typically affects multiple joints. The patient does not have a history of joint symptoms other than the current episode, so rheumatoid arthritis is less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOsteoarthritis \u003C/strong\u003Eis a degenerative joint disease that typically affects weight-bearing joints. The patient\u0027s right knee is swollen and tender, but there on synovial fluid analysis, CPPD crystals are found, which are usually not associated with osteoarthritis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGout \u003C/strong\u003Eis a type of inflammatory arthritis that is caused by the deposition of uric acid crystals in the joints. The patient does not have a history of gout and the joint aspiration does not show uric acid crystals. Gout is therefore less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESeptic arthritis\u003C/strong\u003E is a bacterial infection of the joint. The patient does not have a fever or other systemic symptoms of infection, and the joint aspiration does not show any bacteria. Septic arthritis is therefore less likely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pseudogout is associated with positively birefringent crystals on synovial fluid analysis"],"references":["Rosenthal AK, Ryan LM. Calcium Pyrophosphate Deposition Disease. N Engl J Med. 2016 Jun 30;374(26):2575-84. doi: 10.1056/NEJMra1511117. PMID: 27355536; PMCID: PMC6240444.","Schumacher HR. Crystal-induced arthritis: an overview. Am J Med. 1996 Feb 26;100(2A):46S-52S. doi: 10.1016/s0002-9343(97)89546-0. PMID: 8604727.","Zamora EA, Naik R. Calcium Pyrophosphate Deposition Disease. [Updated 2023 Jun 20]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK540151/","Sidari A, Hill E. Diagnosis and Treatment of Gout and Pseudogout for Everyday Practice. Prim Care. 2018 Jun;45(2):213-236. doi: 10.1016/j.pop.2018.02.004. PMID: 29759121."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62780"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12893"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62780","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62780"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-06T15:27:31+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-06T15:27:31+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5331"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77273"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group